description.narrative: (Jordan): Civic Initiatives Support (CIS) cultivates a strong and vibrant civil society through a broad range of civic initiatives. Currently, the activity is focusing on national and local civil society advocacy efforts in light of the recent passage of the decentralization law. Through CIS, USAID supports local, non-governmental organizations to provide services across sectors and geographic locations. While promoting broad-based, community-driven issues such as inclusion and service delivery, the activity provides targeted assistance and grants to democracy, rights, and governance organizations on issues pertaining to sub-national and local elections. CIS furthers the capacity development for civil society organizations (CSOs) through continued delivery of open courses and targeted training and through the implementation of institutional assessments and technical support. Lastly, CIS provides platforms for CSOs to explore their role in fostering political participation and advancing change.

Objectives for Jordan: In line with USAID’s Country Development Cooperation Strategy (CDCS), CIS is meant to be cross-cutting and support all of CDCS' objectives. It inclusively provides support to civil society actors working in the fields of democracy, human rights and governance, economic development, education, energy, environment, health, and/or water through: Sub-awards and technical assistance in support of Jordanian civic initiatives; Institutional strengthening and capacity building support to CSOs at all levels, including Jordanian intermediary support organizations; Targeted technical assistance to USAID implementing partner sub-award recipients from across the Mission’s portfolio of programs; Enhancing the capacities of Government of Jordan staff at the Registry of Societies and other relevant Ministries that engage with civil society;Funding for research on the civil society sector; Funding for research on the civil society sector; and Supporting opportunities for Government of Jordan-civil society dialogue.
